  <li id="comment-55134" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Liz</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2013/06/told-you-so/#comment-55134"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-06-07T21:26:24-04:00">Tuesday, June 7, 2016 at 9:26 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>FWIW, if you decide to use farro instead, go with 1.5 cups.  I soaked mine for 8 hrs, then prepared it as described.  Delish!</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-65123" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Kristin</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2013/06/told-you-so/#comment-65123"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2017-06-19T13:44:21-04:00">Monday, June 19, 2017 at 1:44 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I never thought the day would come that I was grateful for having run out of mayonnaise but today is that day.  Pulled out pasta, peas and Tina to make a little salad for lunch but realized I was out of mayo.  Try as I might, I don&#8217;t like my homemade mayo as well as Helman&#8217;s (I know, I know).  Then angels sang and I remembered this recipe and I will now probably never make tuna salad again, or any other pasta, at least not for a long, long time.  I used some whole milk (homemade) kefir (not even strained to a yogurty thickness), Parmesan instead of feta, and not enough basil but it was magnificent.  Next time I&#8217;ll use feta because I know it will be delicious, though the Parmesan was delicious too.  The chili oil and pine nuts make it.  Thank you, thank you, thank you.</p>
         
  
